es has largely disappeared, and that older Americans continue to vote more than younger Americans. Leighley and Nagler also show how electoral reforms such as Election Day voter registration and absentee voting have boosted voter turnout, and how turnout would also rise if parties offered more distinct choices. Providing the most systematic analysis available of modern voter turnout, Who Votes Now? reveals that persistent class bias in turnout has enduring political consequences, and that it really does matter who votes and who doesn't.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aElectionszUnited StatesvStatistics. 0aElectionszUnited StatesxStatistics. 0aPolitical participationzUnited StatesvStatistics. 0aPolitical participationzUnited StatesxStatistics. 0aVoter turnoutzUnited StatesvStatistics. 0aVoter turnoutzUnited StatesxStatistics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican National Election Studies.  aCurrent Population Survey.  aU.S presidential elections.  aU.S. Census Bureau.  aU.S. presidential elections.  aabsentee voting.  aconditional relationships.  ademographics.  aelection laws.  aelection reform.  aelectoral reforms.  aelectorate.  aelectrion law.  aincome bias.  ainequality.  anonvoters.  apolicy choices.  apolicy positions.  aredistributive issues.  arepresentation.  astate electoral rules.  avoter behavior.  avoter registration laws.  avoter registration.  avoter representation.  avoter turnout.  avoting.1 aNagler, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400848621zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.de